Kenya Ports Authority are the 2021 Kenya Basketball Federation (KBF) women'sÂ  Premier League basketball champions. The ports women blanked reigning champions Equity Bank 70-64 in a tight play-off Game Four at the Makande Welfare Hall in Mombasa today. It was KPA who bolted away to a 22-10 first-quarter lead but the bankers replied with the fire of their own, taking the second 19-15. The home team were up 35-31 at the break. After resumption, again it was the porters who took the initiative taking a slim 16-13 advantage. But again Equity Bank replied to Lead 20-17 in the deciding stanza.KPA build a 17-point lead at one time but never say die Equity Bank remained unbowed. Both sides had two lead changes and also tied twice. This was the Porters 15th national title and the first since 2017. They bagged a first in 1992, four years after the start of the women league. "It was a tight game. Equity Bank are a worthy opponent. I had a good lead but they closed this to within one point," said KPA coach Antony Ojukwu. "I sensed danger and called time out to stem the tide. My players responded superbly by stopping their offense and pumping in baskets. "This is my trophy. They won it for two years because I was out of the team. Now that I've returned, you can see the result. I've reclaimed it. I am a happy man."Natalie Akinyi and Hilda Indasi led KPA with 16 points apiece while Medina Okot shot 15 and Selina Okumu registered 10. Equity Bank had a game-high of 21 points from Betty Kananu, Melissa Akinyi made 14, and Samba Mjomba chipped in with another 10. KPA won Game Three 77-63 on Saturday to take a 2-1 series lead. The opening two games in Nairobi were split after a 53-51 loss and a 58-45 victory. In Nairobi, Eldonets won the women's Division One title, pipping Jomo Kenyatta University of Agriculture and Technology (Jkuat) Lynx 41-39. 